  "response": "Spain was technically neutral during World War II, though it had sympathies with the Axis powers. Several key factors contributed to Spain's non-involvement:\n\n1. Recent Civil War\n- Spain had just emerged from a devastating civil war (1936-1939)\n- The country was economically and militarily exhausted\n- Francisco Franco wanted to rebuild and recover the nation\n\n2. Franco's Political Position\n- While ideologically aligned with Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy\n- Franco did not want to risk further conflict or potential invasion\n- Maintained a strategic neutrality to preserve Spain's interests\n\n3. Limited Military Capability\n- Spanish military was weakened from the civil war\n- Lacked resources and equipment for major international conflict\n- Not prepared for extensive military engagement\n\n4. Strategic Considerations\n- Wanted to maintain control of its colonial territories\n- Feared potential British naval retaliation\n- Recognized potential vulnerability to Allied intervention\n\n5. Diplomatic Maneuvering\n- Provided some limited support to Axis powers\n- Sent volunteer Blue Division to fight against Soviet Union\n- Maintained diplomatic relations with multiple sides\n\nWhile not actively participating in combat, Spain's position was more complex than simple neutrality, with clear sympathies toward Axis ideological perspectives without direct military involvement.",
